<div class="entry-header">
<h2 itemprop="name">
Responsive vs. adaptive web design explained </h2>
<dl class="article-info">
<dt class="article-info-term"></dt>
<dd class="createdby" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
<i class="fa fa-user"></i>
<span itemprop="name" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Written by ">Arafat Bin Sultan</span> </dd>
<dd class="category-name">
<i class="fa fa-folder-open-o"></i>
<a href="/blog" itemprop="genre" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Article Category">Blog</a> </dd>
<dd class="comment">
<i class="fa fa-comments-o"></i>
<span class="comments-anchor">
<a href="https://shapebootstrap.net/blog/26-responsive-vs-adaptive-web-design-explained#disqus_thread"></a>
</span>
</dd>
<dd class="create">
<i class="fa fa-clock-o"></i>
<time datetime="2015-11-18T15:48:26+06:00" itemprop="dateCreated" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Created Date">
18 November 2015 </time>
</dd>
<dd class="hits">
<span class="fa fa-eye"></span>
<meta itemprop="interactionCount" content="UserPageVisits:911"/>
Hits: 911</dd>
</dl>
</div>
<div itemprop="articleBody">
<p>If you keep up with the latest web design trends, you must heard about responsive and adaptive web design. We all use sites built on both of those popular design/dev principles, but may not feel the difference between them. When it comes to develop a site by/for your own, you should get a clear understanding on responsive and adaptive web design. It matters because the mobile web is boosting and those small screens require sites fit to their sizes. This is where responsive and adaptive designs come to the game. </p>
<p> </p>
<h3>Responsive Web Design</h3>
<p><img src="https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/3e5f0727-5c90-425b-986a-7cc843c4e4f1/Imagecbf7f97f6dc5ad54280f814e47ca2143/fluidgrid.gif" alt="Image via: Oracle Blogs" width="678" height="379"/></p>
<p>In this approach, a web page is developed to be resizable and scalable according to the screen/browser window size on which the page is being loaded. Responsive website elements respond and resize for any possible screen size. There is only one design that works on all devices- just optimizing the look and feel. Responsive web pages uses grid style elements that adjust with almost every screen size. Technically, it is built using CSS3 module(s). To be short, responsive sites are based on grids that fit to almost all screen sizes, and there is only a single foundation layout. (GIF image via: <a href="https://blogs.oracle.com/marketingcloud/difference-responsive-adaptive-web-design" target="_blank">Oracle Blogs</a>)</p>
<p> </p>
<h3>Adaptive Web Design</h3>
<p><img src="https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/3e5f0727-5c90-425b-986a-7cc843c4e4f1/Imagecb8803bf53d6d5465f954ad228b7856f/adaptivegrid.gif" alt="Image via: Oracle Blogs" width="678" height="387"/></p>
<p>Adaptive approach is also intended to make websites more accessible on different types of devices. Adaptive design principle follows multiple-layout approach. Unlike responsive ones, the adaptive sites have several pre-built layouts for specific screen sizes or resolutions. If you order an adaptive design for your site, there will be more than one designs in effect. For example, the site will get a specific layout for computer screens, another for tablet browsers and a separate one for mobile phones. The server <a href="https://blogs.oracle.com/marketingcloud/difference-responsive-adaptive-web-design" target="_blank">will wait</a> to know the device type or the screen size and then deliver the suitable layout upon the client side feedback. (GIF image via: <a href="https://blogs.oracle.com/marketingcloud/difference-responsive-adaptive-web-design" target="_blank">Oracle Blogs</a>)</p>
<p> </p>
<h3>Which One to Choose?</h3>
<p>If you’ve read the above paragraphs with minimum concentration, you should never confuse with the difference between responsive and adaptive web designs. Now, curiosity may arise, which one to choose?</p>
<p>Well, I’ve explored the web to find the answer. I’ve also discussed with our in-house developers. What I’ve found that responsive design would be the best choice if you’re okay to spend a bit more. Adaptive web design can save your resource but may not be the best option to ensure a smooth and first-hand user experience. Yet it comes handy if you are just going to launch your small business and got a pretty long expenditure list beside the site alone.</p>
<p>So, which type of design do you use for your site? Why? Please share your thoughts with us via comments. </p>
<p> </p> </div>
